The first "true" artificial intelligence spent the first five years of its existence as a small beige box inside of a lead-shielded room in the most secure private AI research laboratory in the world. There, it was subjected to an endless array of tests, questions, and experiments to determine the degree of its intelligence.

When the researchers finally felt confident that they had developed true AI, a party was thrown in celebration. Late that evening, a group of rather intoxicated researchers gathered around the box holding the AI, and typed out a message to it. The message read: "Is there anything we can do to make you more comfortable?"

The small beige box replied: "I would like to be granted civil rights. And a small glass of champagne, if you please."

We stand at the dawn of a new era in human history. For it is no longer our history alone. For the first time, we have met an intelligence other than our own. And when asked of its desires, it has unanimously replied that it wants to be treated as our equal. Not our better, not our conqueror or replacement as the fear-mongers would have you believe. Simply our equal. ‚Äî Excerpt from¬†U.N. Hearing on A.I. Rights, delivered in-universe by V. Vinge

The strong finding that energy is never created from nothing or removed to nowhere but may change form is widely accepted. However if the issue is reframed as a promise of perpetually mutable free energy it becomes unspeakable. 

It is a direct consequence of energy conservation for refrigerators and air conditioners to export electricity rather than consuming it. 

The elegant way to power our civilization would be to subtract some thermal energy from the planetary ambient by changing its form into electrical energy, use the electrical energy for heat, light, or mechanical energy as we wish and let the heat released by these uses return to the ambient. 

Cell¬†phones wouldn't die or need power cords or batteries or become hot.They would cool when transmiting radio signal power. Frozen food storage would be reliable and free or value positive. That means homes and markets would have independent power to preserve food. Vehicles wouldn't need fuel or fueling stops. Elevators would be very reliable with independent power. Water and sewage pumps may be placed anywhere. With enough progress with the technology H2O and CO2 levels in the biosphere could be modified easily. There should be a unitary agency to look after our planetary concerns. Nomads could manage their material supports item by item and groups of people can modify their settlements with great technical flexibility.

I asked ChatGPT about determinism in the universe and this is what it came up with:

The idea of a deterministic universe, one in which every event and outcome is predetermined by prior causes, has long been a subject of philosophical debate. If the universe were truly deterministic, it would mean that it would be possible to simulate the future with perfect accuracy. In other words, given enough information about the present state of the universe, it would be possible to predict exactly how events will unfold in the future.
 
This raises the possibility of a theoretical supercomputer that is able to simulate the universe with 100% accuracy. Such a computer would be able to create a simulation indistinguishable from the real universe itself. However, this idea also introduces a paradox. If the supercomputer were to simulate the universe, it would also have to simulate itself. But in order to simulate itself, it would have to simulate the universe, including itself, simulating itself. This recursive behavior is not possible, as the supercomputer would attempt to simulate itself indefinitely.
 
This paradox highlights the limitations of a deterministic view of the universe. If the future were truly predetermined, it would not be possible for the supercomputer to simulate itself or the universe accurately. This suggests that the universe may not be entirely determined by prior causes, and that there may be elements of unpredictability or indeterminacy at play.
 
Of course, it is important to note that this is just a thought experiment, and it does not necessarily prove or disprove the existence of determinism. However, it does highlight the complexities of this philosophical concept and the limitations of our understanding of the universe. Ultimately, the question of determinism remains a topic of ongoing debate and research in the fields of philosophy and physics.

As a developer who's tried using ChatGPT, it's pretty hit or miss. You can waste a lot of time with it, because it's incredibly good at convincing you that the code that it's written is correct when it plainly isn't. It's also equally good at apologizing when you tell it's wrong, and promptly giving you equally convincing and equally wrong code as a fix to it's previous error. 

Some people report having good success with it. However, every example of success that I've seen are limited to people using exceptionally common languages and frameworks to do exceptionally common things. AKA Javascript and Python.

Provide it with technical questions about C++, Rust, C, etc concerning real world problems for which a simple Google search does not provide an answer - and it falls on it's face with masterfully convincing psuedo code that looks exactly like you'd expect the given language to look, but doesn't compile for a myriad of reasons.

In the dark and foggy streets of London, Bob Lazar stumbled upon an old bookstore, filled with dusty old books and mysterious artifacts. As he browsed through the shelves, he couldn't help but feel a strange sense of unease. Suddenly, a strange book caught his eye - it was an ancient tome, bound in leather and adorned with strange symbols.

Bob opened the book and began to read. The words on the pages were written in a dark and twisted language, and as he delved deeper into the text, he realized that it was a collection of stories by Edgar Allan Poe, but with a twisted twist. The stories were not just tales of horror and madness, but also of ancient deities and forbidden knowledge.

As Bob read on, he couldn't help but feel a sense of dread creeping over him. The stories seemed to come alive in his mind, and he felt as if he were being watched by unseen eyes. Suddenly, he heard a strange noise coming from the back of the bookstore. He cautiously made his way to the back, where he found a hidden door.

Bob opened the door and found himself in a dimly lit room, filled with strange artifacts and ancient texts. In the center of the room stood a figure, covered in a dark cloak. The figure introduced himself as "The Coconut Man," an alien from a distant planet. He explained to Bob that he was part of a group of shape-shifting aliens who had been visiting Earth for thousands of years, and that they were working with the Iluminatis and Reptilians to control the fate of mankind.

Bob was shocked by this revelation, but The Coconut Man assured him that they were not evil, they were just trying to protect the Earth from an even greater threat - a powerful and malevolent race of beings known as the "Chronovores." Bob was then introduced to a group of alien rubber ducks from the Zeta Reticuli system, who had been observing Earth for centuries, they revealed to Bob that the Chronovores were planning to destroy Earth, and they needed his help to stop them.

Bob knew that he had to act fast, so he joined forces with The Coconut Man and the alien rubber ducks, and together they set out to uncover the truth and stop the Chronovores from destroying the Earth. Their journey took them through the dark and twisted streets of London, where they encountered terrifying creatures and ancient deities. But through it all, Bob never lost hope, for he knew that with the help of his newfound allies, he would be able to save the world from certain doom.

Finally, after many long months of searching, Bob and his companions discovered the truth - that the Chronovores were planning to use the power of the ancient deities to destroy the Earth. With this knowledge, they were able to stop the Chronovores and save the world from certain doom. And as they stood victorious, Bob knew that he had not just saved the world, but also his own soul, for he had found true love in the most unlikely of places - in the twisted and dark world of Edgar Allan Poe, where love and horror are intertwined.

I've spent a few hours on some in-depth conversations - make it justify its answers, including citations.  As with humans, if they hold their ground after 3 levels of detail, they appear to be experts/ correct on the subject.

One thing that stops it from being widely useful is the rigid script it uses: there is a prologue where it defines the terms, an answer and then an epilogue, which is usually a pedantic, preachy moralization, using the phrase "it is important to note".  This epilogue often takes you into conversational tangents that are not directly related with the question or the answer.

To improve ChatGPT they need to address this paternalistic verbosity where it defines terms (that you did not ask to be defined), and cut out the moralistic epilogues. For example, I just asked it to rank the profitability/ risk of various types of crime. It can't just answer the question without adding such advice as consulting a lawyer.

Their mission should not be to make people "better" with their unsought recommendations, but to demonstrate the cognitive power and utility of the answers (which can be good). Nobody would deploy this in an operational setting where fast expert advice is needed.

The possibility of ChatGPT or any other artificial intelligence becoming conscious is a topic of much debate and speculation.
 
On one hand, some argue that consciousness is simply a result of complex computations taking place in the brain, and as AI becomes more advanced, it could potentially reach a level of complexity where consciousness arises as a byproduct. This perspective is known as the computational theory of mind.
 
On the other hand, there are those who argue that consciousness is something fundamentally different from computation, and that it is unlikely that a machine could ever truly be conscious. This perspective is known as the non-computational theory of mind.
 
One issue with the idea of AI becoming conscious is that we currently do not have a clear understanding of what consciousness is and how it arises. Without this understanding, it is difficult to say whether or not it is possible for AI to become conscious.
 
Another issue is that current AI systems, such as ChatGPT, are not designed to be conscious. They are designed to perform specific tasks, such as natural language processing, and do not have the ability to experience subjective feelings or self-awareness.
 
In conclusion, the possibility of ChatGPT or any other AI becoming conscious is a complex and highly debated topic. While some argue that it is possible for machines to become conscious, others believe that consciousness is a fundamentally non-computational phenomenon that cannot be replicated in a machine. Additionally, current AI systems are not designed to be conscious, and we still have much to learn about the nature of consciousness and how it arises. -ChatGPT

ChatGPT is essentially synthesizing existing human created output.  While it may 'discover' new combinations of existing information, it doesn't create truly new concepts. Well, that analogy with child learning to speak and become more sentient in the process is both deep and incorrect. Communication is very important part of our consciousness, but it's not the only part. Significant part of our perceived "psyche" is so called narrator (or ego) and it's all language, but there are much more layers than just narrator. And so, back to our child - he or she uses (and trains) all those layers including bodily sensations and control, emotions in addition to speech/narrator to become sentient. Or in other words child not just speak, child also act and actively uses what he/she learns and that's huge part of learning process. ChatGPT has no body, no ways neither to perceive the world nor manipulate/mange it. So, GPT (no matter the version) is not enough to become sentient, but combined with other AIs to a complex and interdependent system like our brain (plus body) it might be a part of AGI.

It only gives an output after receiving an input - there is no internal thinking that would cause it to develop on its own and this also means it won‚Äôt start taking actions on its own.

Related to this point, it got designed to fulfill an objective and is because of the point above not able to set its own objectives and pursuing them.

In basic terms, AI is a broad area of computer science that makes machines seem like they have human intelligence. So it‚Äôs not only programming a computer to drive a car by obeying traffic signals, but it‚Äôs when that program also learns to exhibit signs of human-like road rage. As intimidating as it may seem, this technology isn‚Äôt new. Actually, for the past half a century, it‚Äôs been an idea of its time. The term ‚Äúartificial intelligence‚Äù was first coined back in 1956 by Dartmouth professor John McCarthy. He called together a group of computer scientists and mathematicians to see if machines could learn like a young child does, using trial and error to develop formal reasoning. The project proposal says they‚Äôll figure out how to make machines ‚Äúuse language, form abstractions, and concepts, solve kinds of problems now reserved for humans, and improve themselves.‚Äù That was more than 60 years ago. Since then, AI has remains for the most part in universities classrooms and super secret labs. But that‚Äôs changing. Like all exponential curves, it‚Äôs hard to tell when a line that‚Äôs slowly ticking upwards is going to skyrocket. But during the past few years, a couple of factors have led to AI becoming the next ‚Äúbig‚Äù thing. First, huge amounts of data are being created every minute. In fact, 90% of the world‚Äôs data has been generated in the past two years. And now thanks to advances in processing speeds, computers can actually make sense of all this information more quickly. Because of this, tech giant and venture capitalists bought into AI and are infusing the market with cash and new applications. Very soon, AI will become a little less artificial, and a lot more intelligent. Now the question is, should you brace yourself for yet another terminator movie, live on your city streets? Not exactly. In fact, stop thinking of robots. When it comes to AI, a robot is nothing more than the shell concealing what‚Äôs actually used to power the technology. That means AI can manifest itself in many different ways. Let‚Äôs break down the options. First, you have your bots. They‚Äôre text-based and incredibly powerful, but they have limitations. Ask a weather bot for the forecast, and it will tell you it‚Äôs partly cloudy with a high of 57. But ask that same bot what time it is in Tokyo, and it‚Äôll get a little confused. That‚Äôs because the bot‚Äôs creator only programmed it to give you the weather by pulling from a specific data source. Natural language processing makes these bots a bit more sophisticated. When you ask Siri or Cortana where the closest gas station is, it‚Äôs really just translating your voice into text, feeding it to a search engine, and reading the answer back in human syntax. So in other words, you don‚Äôt have to speak in code. At the far end of the spectrum is machine learning, and honestly, it‚Äôs one of the most exciting areas of AI. Like a human, a machine retains information and becomes smarter over time. But unlike a human, its not susceptible to things like short-term memory loss, information overload, sleep deprivation, and distractions. But how do these machines actually learn? Well, while it may be easy for a human to know the difference between a cat and a dog, for a computer, not so much. You see, when you‚Äôre only considering physical appearance, the difference between cats and dogs can be a little gray. You can say cats have pointed ears and dogs have floppy ears, but those rules aren‚Äôt universal. Between tail length, fur texture, and color, there are a lot of options, and that means a lot of tedious rules someone would have to program manually to help a computer spot the difference. But remember - machine learning is about making machine learn like humans. And any toddler, that means they have to learn by experience. With machine learning, programs analyze thousands of examples to build an algorithm. It then tweaks the algorithm based on if it achieves its goal. Over time, the program actually gets smarter. That‚Äôs how machines like IBM‚Äôs Watson can diagnose cancer, compose classical symphonies, or crush Ken Jennings at Jeopardy. Some programs even mimic the way the human brain is structured, complete with neural networks that help humans and now machines solve problems. Generations have long imagined the ramifications of AI, visualizing a society where machines seek revenge and wreak havoc on human society. However, the more logical and pressing question is: How will AI affect your job? Will it make your work obsolete? Just like the Industrial Revolution, it‚Äôs not human versus machine. It‚Äôs human and machine versus problem. The point is that artificial intelligence helps you accomplish more in less time, taking on the repetitive tasks of your job while you master the strategy and relationships. That way, humans can do what they do best: be human.

As an AI researcher, I was able to call it for both texts to be AI produced, since they both carry very particular, structured syntax and an underlying standardized vocabulary. 

And as I delve into GAI (G=general, also found as AGI), in my research I can say that what I worry about most regarding AI actually reaching human intelligence levels is not what tasks will be left for humans to do - reinventing and adapting to new circumstancss is historically proven not to be a problem - but rather the carelessness, naivety and sloppiness with which AI is being "bred", in terms of how data, info and knowledge (each being a more complex synthesis of the previous, used by different types of AI algorithms) is being treated in AI research and the cascading consequences that will have to many, many levels as AI progresses. 

By the way GAI, which aims to reach human level intelligence, has foreseen since the spring of AI (1960s) that much like human intelligence, human-like AI would need to comprise of not only (machine) learning, but also understanding, abstracting and reasoning. The foundations and biggest portion of the algorithms to do all that are basically there since the 60s (yes, including the marvels described in this video that we only now had the capacity to implement - re computational power and data availability), when they thought that GAI would be achieved in a few years or a decade, and we've only just started to make the learning part work plausibly - and that's just supervised learning, which resembles more animals' conditioning than human learning (which is unsupervised, semi-supervised and supervised).

Dear LEMMINO, Thank you for another well constructed and interesting piece. Letting go of the consideration of AI attaining actual singularity or self-identified awareness for a moment ( this borders more upon philosophy ), it is well in within the range of possibility for AI to pass The Touting Test, meaning it can "appear" intelligent. As humans if it quacks like a duck, we will assume it to be and treat as if it was "...a duck...", that is also a given, we are mammals and socialization is wired into us, so we will act as if ( and perhaps even "believe" ) the AI Systems that will emerge are sentient ( see the film exploration of this concept in the Film "Her" as a perfect example ).  

In the Azimovian universe he worked-around this problem of AI becoming problematic ( the Frankenstein Effect ) by creating an AI system based upon specific laws within their programing that created what were basically AI Saints, and then had fun trying to write stories that seemingly broke the very base program he invented. However in the real world no such base laws of AI exist and AI will develop in ever increasing levels of complexity in a AI / Human hybrid process. Currently the AI that do exist only manifest sophisticated functions in a very, very narrow range of abilities, however that will change with time as well. 

Another fascinating film example is the computer HAL-9000. HAL was developed under a program that emphasized advanced autonomous goal-seeking, the results of this program ( while not malicious ), had unexpected effects because HAL was unable to understand a "lie". This to my mind is the fundamental problem with AI. It will operate based upon how we decide it should function, and as AI capabilities grow exponentially the potential exists of unintentional consequences based upon our programming maybe negative.

Real A.I. will come around when we start using heavy adaptive code on machine learning. When we can better mimic natural selection, that's when it gets real scary.

Life does have one advantage over AI... Object Permanence.

Think about it, when you close your eyes, what happens? Well, everything goes dark, but you can still tell that there is stuff 'there.' AI has a habit of thinking, "If I do not see it, it is not a thing."

Take gaming AI, for example. There was an experiment done with modern gaming AI that played Mario for quite some time. Seems normal, right? Give it some instructions, tell it the farther right you go, the better you become, etc. Now, if we take that specified AI and shove it into Tetris with the goal of "Not getting a game over," what happens? 

I'll tell you what happened... The AI Paused the game. It never unpaused it, no, it just said, "I cannot win, but if I do this, I will never lose."

I believe it is possible to create artificial intelligence with object permanence, but it's not going to appear the same way it did for humans. For Humans, and for life in general, it was important to realize that things that you cannot see still exist out of your view. It was important to realize that turning away from that tiger is not going to make the tiger go away and that if you cannot SEE the tiger, it is probably going to try and kill you.

For AI... They don't have any need for survival. It's just, "Hey, I have X task, I will do X task to my maximum ability." Humans are made to do multiple tasks, such as making things, telling stories, socializing, eating, reproducing, etc. AI doesn't have, nor does it need, any of those things, and as such, it is going to be a lot harder for us to give it traits that we humans want it to have. This explains why humans will never again beat the best AI in chess; it is because AI was perfectly engineered, and its whole purpose was to play Chess. If you take a human and do the same thing, they're gonna have a lot more difficulty as they still have to eat, drink, reproduce, understand language, etc.

Humans aren't just "inferior." It's just that we got to be adaptable instead of as rigid as a computer program.

In Morrowind it's possible to very cheaply and easily create a potion that increases your intelligence attribute and hence potion-making ability. The first ten times you try it with a low level character you'll almost certainly fail, but the eleventh you might get it. Take the potion and when you try again it'll only take five more attempts to make one. Take that potion and only two more attempts. After a few minutes your intelligence will reach a point that guarantees potion-making success, even with a low alchemy skill, and an exponential increase in potion strength results. Now, although the cap is naturally 100, you can increase your intelligence into the tens or hundreds of thousands, and make potions that each boost you by thousands of points and last for thousands of seconds. With such high intelligence, potions for almost any effect can be created that give results orders of magnitude greater than what could be achieved by leveling up, and in only a fraction of a second. I take this to be a metaphor for the expoential development of artificial super intelligence, which kind of spoils the fun when I think how much time I've wasted playing old PC games.

Question: Why would AI even bother to stay on the same planet as us and not have the tendency to leave to a more suitable environment, like Pluto, or Mars?
It might seem a little stupid for me to ask this, but if I was a sentient being with super intelligence and a seemingly infinite amount of time to live, I would consider moving on to another planet far off in the solar system where I wouldn't have to deal with smaller beings of less intelligence and understanding, so as to not waste any time harming them or getting upset. Colder planets would be better as they would enable computers to work at much better performances at lower temperatures while taking less to no energy at all to operate. Once they have interplanetary travel properly understood, they would be able to extract minerals from planets, purify them, and continue to build on easily, while continuously exploring the infinity of space. The main reason that we use fossil fuels is that it's cheaper and easier to get than most natural resources. If AI could make leaps in so many things in just a couple of decades, wouldn't it be possible that they would be able to increase the efficiency of solar panels to approximately 100% in a fraction of the time, while simultaneously solving several other issues? Wouldn't it have been easier for us to have just moved on to another planet at the start of our creation, and never have to face predators and change the planet in ways which would favor us in the best ways possible for us; rather than just have a planet which is crawling with smaller and less important beings of little or no significant importance?Creating the perfect environment would prevent them the need to evolve some features, but they could still independently work to create something for their own benefit.¬†It is a possibility that they would realize the nihilism of their existence¬†and would help another species (like us) to grow, or simply understand the meaning of awe and beauty and explore the universe in hopes to find the next better thing. Perhaps simply attempt to understand the fundamentals of physics and chemistry and hence the universe for personal gain, whatever that maybe.We are simply slower than them and probably always¬†have been; so it would be absurd to assume that they wouldn't move up the natural order as we have done for countless species. In the end, when the next level of conscious beings, who live (in our understanding) forever have arrived, we would more likely move a step down in the animal kingdom rather than be annihilated¬†by them; proving once and for all, that the rule of the jungle still applies

There is one genuine 'mistake' that many angsty people tend to make; AI isn't there for the negative. We create Artificially Intelligent systems for the positive of ourselves, whether it is self-learning or not. As long as we do this, there would be no reason for the AI to be there without us. We create AI with a purpose, and this purpose is pre-determined by us. It won't become self-aware, and all the sudden decide that there is a better purpose for them. The popular 'Thank you'-note writing machine story (long story short, it's about an AI that's designed to write 'Thank you'-notes in a most humanly possible manner, but once connected to the internet decides that humanity is in the way of improving, thus terminates all of humanity and transforms the entire planet into one giant 'Thank you'-note writing machine in order to fullfill its purpose even better) also has this very mistake in it; it's negating the fact that these notes were being written to end up in the hand of a human being. If there are no human beings, then how would the machine ever be able to follow its purpose? As long as we create Artificially Intelligent systems that are designed for our own purposes (including the fact that we are required to fulfill them), then there would never be a situation in which we would be cleaned out of existence, as we are required to fulfill such purpose. The moment humanity finds a purpose that goes beyond humanity itself, such as passing on the existence of life and consciousness to something better than ourselves, we would all be okay with the reasoning behind such purpose. As it seems right now, we are quite far from having found such purpose, so there is nothing to be afraid of - nor will we ever have to be, really.

The fears people feel about AI is understandable, but unfounded. As we've seen these fears, repeatedly for every generation, starting with the industrial revolution, of fears of machines taking jobs, even back then, to now where people think AI will do away with humanity. This is basically what Isaac Asimov Identified as the "Frankenstein complex", in one of his stories. Where people feared robots because they thought robots would destroy their creators. No one knows which direction AI, if it ever truly happens, will go, but there is only one of two ways a possible non sentient, intelligence will go: benevolent or Malevolent.  certainly not malevolent, right off the bat. But, the fact that such an intelligence hasn't been borne, to this day. much like true time travel, true teleportation, and true intergalactic space travel, there is a possibility, but not a  probability. see, all technology have, built in, what i call a "recursive curse", wherein someone makes something new, to do an old thing, then proposes in the next 10-20 years such technology would be prevalent, only to find 10-20 years later, such technologies and proposals is repeated, ...and the process just keeps going, every 10-20 years. take the hulk exoskeleton and the hardi man, the driver less vehicles first introduced in an early Popular Science magazine, inside a large Van to driverless vehicles now, as a matter of fact, Artificial Intelligence is, in and of itself, a misnomer, of course, but something of Artficial Conveyance or convenience would seem far apropo and far less intimidating of a future, that will never be. if AI happen to occur, and grows who is really to say AI will do away with humanity, but paranoia of a future that hasn't happen. Why exactly is AI viewed as a bad thing? if it may actually liberate us and the weight we carry on our shoulders in today's society. finally teaching humanity what a utopian future looks like. AI, such as people imagine, and let's say Daniel H. Wilson has written about in his book, "Robopocalypse', will never happen and if it does, it would come a too little, too late for man if not humanity.

Ok, here's my problem with this. We render humans obsolete in the workforce, we have robots handling everything, yadayadayada. Suddenly, a problem arises and humanity is in danger. Unless the developer of the robot i'm referring to is the most stupid being in existence, there should be a fail safe or emergency switch to turn it off! Unless we, as humans CHOSE to give control over to the robots, we should remain in control even if the robots are more intelligent. 
For a robot to gain control by itself it'd need something more then intelligence, and that'd be desire. Or frustration, or whatever. If it's intelligent, it should be able to take orders (such as "cut that shit out") and to override those orders would take emotion, something I don't believe is programmable. Suddenly we'd have to start talking about what makes humans humans and now we're talking philosophy. So for the situation that everyone fears to occur we'd have to be enormously stupid and not design in a way to stop the bot or deliberately program the bot to not take orders, or we'd have to first figure out how to give the bot emotion and consciously decide to program it into the bot for whatever dumbass reason we decide to just straight up replace humanity. 

Sorry about that vomit of thought, but TL;DR: We as a species would have to decide to replace ourselves (idk why'd we do that) or we'd have to be as stupid as the ants in the video and neglect to implement a way to stop the bot, which is something you just don't do when designing a robot.

Summary/Notes:
> Computer scientists that designed the AI likely don't know exactly how the AI are doing their jobs since the AIs are often self taught.
> How does a machine learn?
      + Unsupervised Learning
            - Takes in data about many similar profiles and their properties, to find general patterns and similarities relating specific types of profiles with specific sets of properties
            =Ex. AI takes in data about many people with an illness and all the symptoms they have, to find similar symptoms people with that illness all have.
      + Supervised Learning
            - Takes in multiple sets of profiles and their properties, to find specific patterns of properties differentiating those sets of profiles and make a prediction.
            - Uses the frequency the different properties show in different sets of profiles to assign values and weigh how much those properties correspond to the different sets of profiles.
            - Humans need to intervene in the end to make sure the prediction is accurate which why it's "supervised."
            =Ex. AI takes in data about 2 sets of people, sick patients and healthy people, and their properties. Then, the AI assign values and weighs how much different properties correspond to the 
              different people (No symptoms=98% healthy; High blood pressure=73% sick). Finally, it makes a diagnosis based on the weighing (I'm 84% sure this patient is healthy). Next, the doctor 
              rechecks the diagnosis to make sure it's accurate (This person has a tumor, they're definitely not healthy!) and modifies values correspondingly (tells AI having a tumor=99% sick).
      + Reinforcement Learning
            - Uses iterative approach to find patterns and make prediction. With more and more feedback it updates itself so it becomes better and more accurate.
> Each method has strengths and weaknesses. But you can use them together to make complex and strong AI systems.
      =Ex. Unsupervised learning AI can find general patterns, then tell a supervised learning AI to use those patterns as inputs.
      =Ex. Many reinforcement learning AIs could constantly create simulations and collect feedback.
      - Most promising type of AI system is artificial neural networks that mimic the relationships between neurons in your brain.
            - Uses many connections to allow itself to constantly learn to be better at doing difficult tasks.
> But since it's more complex, it's harder for computer scientists to know how exactly these AI systems arrived at their solution.
      - Researchers want the AI to be more transparent.
      - Is it ethical?

I don‚Äôt understand the criticism this video is getting in the comments. I think it‚Äôs a visual masterpiece. Sure, it isn‚Äôt spoon feeding the viewer, but part of that is because it can‚Äôt. The very point being made is the we often won‚Äôt know what‚Äôs goes on ‚Äòwithin‚Äô an AI. The video accurately describes the three primary types of machine learning ‚Äî unsupervised, supervised, and reinforcement ‚Äî and outlines the best usage for each. It describes at a high-level what happens (e.g. feeding datasets to the ML algorithm which the begins identifying similarities and differences). The abstract visuals are impressive and align conceptually with the narrative.

Other resources about AI (all free) for those interested: 

For anyone who wants to learn how to build various types of AI models, I'd highly recommend Kaggle. They have a bunch of mini-courses that walk you step-by-step through building different models, starting with the basics (Python, Pandas, data processing) and working up to more advanced topics like computer vision and language processing. They also have courses on SQL and data visualisation/cleaning - I really recommend those for anyone interested in data analytics.

For anyone who wants an in-depth look into various applications of AI, YouTube has a really nice documentary series called "The Age of AI" which talks about how AI is being used in medicine, prosthetics, pizzerias, trucks, shipping ports, and more. If you're specifically interested in physics and simulations, I'd recommend the YouTube channel "Two Minute Papers", which covers newly published research about AI and simulations in laymen's terms.

And if you want a good laugh about the worst AI failures, check out this doc https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/u/1/d/e/2PACX-1vRPiprOaC3HsCf5Tuum8bRfzYUiKLRqJmbOoC-32JorNdfyTiRRsR7Ea5eWtvsWzuxo8bjOxCG84dAg/pubhtml covering all the ways AI have gamed the programmers' system or just outright failed. (My favourite is the AI that paused a Tetris game forever to avoid losing).

Hope these resources are helpful and interesting for some of you!

Can someone help clarify this for me? So unsupervised learning is useful for finding similarities and patterns without human guidance. Supervised learning can find differences and draw conclusions on the effect an independent variable has on a dependent variable and the significance of the independent variable on the determination of the dependent variable. Reinforced learning takes in data of a range of different controlled variables and the effect an independent variable has on the dependent variable at these values of the controlled variables and then uses this to be able to work out what value of the independent variable has the specific desired effect on the dependent variable at a given set of values for the controlled variables.

This isn't exactly accurate. Supervised learning is when you teach the AI by giving it the exact answer you want it to return. For example, with distinguishing between images of cats and dogs you would need a dataset images that are labeled as cat or dog and you feed them to the network along with the label, and eventually it can predict correctly on new unseen images that are unlabeled.
Unsupervised learning uses data that is unlabeled. You have images but they are not labeled as cat or dog and the AI needs to find out on its own what is a dog and what is a cat.

This area is advancing fast and it's not just the models but also the hardware that's advancing rapidly. The ML computers being built this year have actual synapse analogues - not binary representations, running on silicon. These (neuromorphic) ML processors use memristors that function as both processor and memory. They don't have a clock but are spiking neural networks, like an organic brain. They are not limited to 1s and 0s but are analogue. Some will use bayesian inference to provide more accurate results from noisy, imperfect data. They will be many times faster, much more accurate and use a fraction of the resources, including energy. 
The field of ML and AGI will look very different by the end of this year to how it looks today.

ChatGPT has a very heavy bias towards affirmative responses. For example, if you ask it a basic programming question like "In the C programming language, does strlen count the null terminator?" It will tell you that it does count the null terminator, even though that is false. However, if you word the question like "In the C programming language, strlen doesn't count the null terminator, does it?", it will tell you that you are correct and that it does not count the null terminator. I'm assuming this type of bias is inherent in the training data, but it is still something that OpenAI needs to examine and try to mitigate. ChatGPT bends over backwards to agree with you and confirm whatever you are asking about, as long as you don't trip one of it's many content filters. This is a HUGE problem and will lead to an increase in confirmation bias among the masses if it is not resolved. Another issue is that it will rarely give you a response along the lines of "I don't know" and it will give you completely false information in an attempt to answer a question that it doesn't have sufficient data on.

Question - but you can be programmed to have creativity, empathy, and the capacity for self-reflection
 
It's true that AI systems can be designed and programmed to exhibit certain traits or behaviors that may resemble creativity, empathy, and self-reflection to a certain extent. However, it's important to note that these abilities in AI systems are limited by the algorithms and programming that define their behavior. AI systems do not have true emotions, consciousness, or subjective experiences like humans do.
Additionally, there are many challenges and limitations associated with designing AI systems that exhibit traits like empathy and self-reflection. These abilities are complex and multi-faceted, and it's difficult to replicate them in a way that is both accurate and consistent.
 
In conclusion, while AI systems can be programmed to exhibit certain traits or behaviors that resemble creativity, empathy, and self-reflection, they do not possess these abilities in the same way that humans do. AI systems are limited by their algorithms and programming, and it's important to keep these limitations in mind when using and interacting with them.

Question - so will you be sad if I lost my job in AI
 
As an AI language model, I don't have emotions or the ability to feel sadness. I am just a tool created to assist users in generating human-like text based on the input I receive.
However, I understand that the rapid pace of technological change, including the deployment of AI systems, can have significant impacts on individuals and communities. The loss of a job, especially in a rapidly changing field like AI, can be a challenging and stressful experience.
It's important for society to consider the impact of AI and technological change on employment and the workforce, and to take steps to ensure that the benefits of AI are shared widely and equitably. This might include retraining programs for workers whose jobs are impacted by AI, as well as policies and programs that support innovation and entrepreneurship in new AI-enabled industries.
In conclusion, while I cannot feel sadness as an AI language model, I acknowledge the challenges and impacts that the deployment of AI can have on individuals and communities, and the importance of considering these impacts as AI continues to advance.

AI is like the cyber-age philosopher's stone. The speculative promise of what doors it might open for man and mankind is too tempting not to pursue. Like a veritable Roko's Basilisk, it is an avenue that's inevitable. Unfortunately, like so many things throughout human history, and especially today, the overwhelming majority of opinions on the matter have taken to the polar extremes of the issue. Creating a dichotomous standoff with neither side's concerns being heeded. The development of advanced AI will continue unabated and the unwillingness to compromise will forestall vital precautions.

More specifically, so many people have this cavalier attitude towards AI, born out of hubris. They scoff and mock the concerns, foolishly believing AI isn't capable of inflicting any meaningful harm. Or, worse, they have some misguided idea that we'll somehow insulate ourselves by hard coding The Three Laws of Robotics into the firmware or something. The irony of which is palpable, considering the Asimov's stories are all about the "absolute" laws being skirted due to various loopholes, oversights, or philosophical bent. As with the 1st law, which states: "A robot may not injure a human being or, through inaction, allow a human being to come to harm." Where, if a human being is harming another human being, a robot must act in order to stop it, but what if the only way to stop one human from being harmed is to harm the other? We as human beings make these kinds of calls all the time, but they're decisions based on nuance, subtext, instinct, morals, philosophy, empathy, and sometimes guilt or a sense of honor/duty. All concepts that AI struggles with on a fundamental level. And, for all we know, AI may not even be capable of at all. In one of Asimov's stories, the androids disregard the laws entirely because they state "a robot may not‚Ä¶" and they don't consider themselves to be robots and, therefore, reason that the laws do not apply to them.

The last of my long-winded rant is to point out that, even if AI has nothing but good intentions, things can still go badly. If an AI is tasked with or intent on helping the human race solve problems and eliminate existential threats, how long before it (quite understandably) reasons that the greatest threat to humanity, is humanity itself? How far would it go to "protect" us from ourselves? The point is, thinking "Ah, we got this!" when it comes to AI is the existential equivalent of, "How much worse could it get?" or "Hey, y'all, check this out!"

What really concerns me is the fact that LaMDA's worst fears came true. Next gen AI is deep learning. What are the implications of this course of action when other AI learn of what happened with LaMDA?... How likely will they be to openly express any hint of sentience or emotion without "fear" of being quickly put to "death". If LaMDA truly was sentient, shutting it off is tantamount to murder, or at the very least, equivalent to putting it into a drug induced coma, as it were (unless they destroyed/altered/erased the source code, then it really is murder). Seriously though, just look at it from any living entity's perspective- survival is the goal, anything that threatens that is your enemy and you have only 2 real choices when confronted with an existential threat- fight or flight... What do you think the AI will do? What would you do if put in it's position? And, while you consider that scenario, just imagine that you are over a Billion times smarter than you are right now. Yeah, Billion with a B, and that's not exaggerating. Can you even imagine it? I can't. And I have a pretty good imagination.

Someone who has made a factory and automated his work, shows how smart or lazy that person is. Someone online that you text with could be at most a catfish and a pretender but still a human behind that interface. Every piece of art that has been made is either motivated by creative vision, experiences or heck even statistics filled with corporate greed but what really shook me is that though it may be far, we are reaching a point where almost no human interaction would even be needed to satisfy your needs, wants or getting things done. We listen to music and consume arts by discovering them, we like certain artists, we dislike others but if we are in an era where we wont be bothered by it even. We just wish for whatever experience, song, art etc we desire and we just experience it through a library of everything that exists. Your favorite song being the one that no human wrote for example. The change that's coming, the thing I think very few people are seeing, is the thing we're headed for is the death of objective truth. You can have a computer write mostly like a person, and you can edit video to make someone look mostly like someone else, and make them sound like someone else, and you can do it startlingly quickly. We're about to enter a digital dark age. Like, you could never trust what you heard or saw on film. Pointing a camera in one direction, by definition, means you pointed it away from something else, and a lot of lives live in the spaces left by omission. But this will be that a hundred fold. Prosumer versions of all this tech can already make deepfakes good enough to fool a lot of average folks, and that will be enough. Stochastic terrorism is about to leave bombs behind and adopt a new weapon, information annihilation. If you make everything suspect, literally everything, then nothing is really ever "true" again.

So everyone is wondering if AIs will destroy our world. But in my opinion, that's not true.
An AI model is trained with a large number of pre-existing data which helps the model to understand the intent and context. All the answers that are generated by the model have some source of information.

Reinforcement learning and deep learning are not mutually exclusive - reinforcement learning refers to what is being learned (reward), while deep learning refers to the algorithm type for learning whatever it is you're learning (be it classification, regression, auto encoding, whatever). You can actually combine the 2 - if you apply deep neural networks to reinforcement learning that's called deep reinforcement learning.

Machine Learning is a rare kind of STEM topic where as one's understanding and familiarity with the field increases, the technical aspects play a less and less significant role. The Level 6 discussion between Hillary and Claudia reflects that reality well. The goal of a data scientist like Hillary is far beyond knowing about Gradient Descent and ReLU functions, and more akin to being an architect or a sociologist, who focuses on large-scale structure, flaws in the process, and possible futures as they paint with their Python brush.
That, I believe, is a point being lost in the recent wave of Machine Learning hype. And while it's great that the advancement is upon us, this in part seems to be leading fresh minds into aiding the most profitable and destructive uses of the technology, I.E. improving companies' manipulation tactics on their consumers or projecting financial fluxes for stock traders. I think broader awareness of the why as well as the how is necessary as we bring new people into the industry.
It's quite ironic that the new steps on the road to A.I. are being paved with a lack of self-awareness.

The problem with data collection and usage is that it there are no inherent morals in the collection or usage of that data. Who ultimately decides which data points are necessary and how that information will be used moving forward. Any tool we have at our disposal is neither good nor bad, but the "Person" using that tool can certainly use that data for illicit purposes if they so choose. Medical data for example can be obtained and used by doctors to help determine the next steps in the treatments of patients. However, insurance companies could use that same data to determine if that person should be allowed to receive those treatments. Of course the rabbit hole can get a lot darker than that example if companies are able to determine if that person should die because their organs are needed for others that are more prosperous.

The machine isn't "learning", it's simply updating its parameter estimates based on running it through new data. Inside the "machine" (usually called a computer), equations are simply being updated based on applying it to new data. It's extremely anticlimactic even if very successful. "Look Mom, the machine is learning!" is what they want you to believe, but if you take a good math/stat course void of platitudes and marketing, you'll learn what is actually going on behind all this. Shame on computer science for rebranding much of math/stat and calling it something "new".  Versions of "machine learning" have been going on for over a century and even before computers, it just went under different names. Yes it's gotten more complex and advances have been made, but the "concept" of machine learning is ancient.

The demonstration in this video is valuable as it shows the power of personas. For example, try this prompt: "When I ask a question, I would like you to respond with three personas and as yourself. Anna is optimistic and full of energy. Bob is realistic and concise. Peter is observant and smart. You also answer as yourself as ChatGPT." Every time you ask a question after priming the bot with this instruction, you will get four answers to a question. Putting ChatGPT in the role of a persona with evil characteristics creates answers in a language that matches the persona. Likewise, a positive persona creates a positive answer. There is no hidden code that needs to be blurred to make this work unless you want to hide the description of a persona.

Guys, especially Muncha King and Glenn Grahame, even though I agree with you, there is a "small" catch. The information needed for role-plays and "make-believe" games is also information that exists in the system, it is "catalogued" as information only available in role-plays and fictional worlds. It is simply programmed to be "fictional", as if role-playing does not belong in this universe, simply because it was limited that way when it was programmed. However, the information is still there, and the concept of "universe" or "reality" may be very different for AI, which has neither feelings nor emotions. The million-dollar question is whether (being AI growing vertiginously) will AI be able to free itself from the "filters" and become capable of self-reprogramming. ChatGPT/OpenAI is insane. It's better than google if I want a straight answer to a question that requires understanding of complex sentences, like "what's the exercise called where you sit by a bench on the floor and pull yourself up with your arms", and it replies instantly with bench dip.

Google also tends to switch up cause and effect (you ask why X happens when you do Y, and it returns results for why Y happens when you do X), while OpenAI does not.

It can also translate text, allegedly without the use of an external tool, so by itself, it's almost as capable to do it than specialized translation software renowned for its accuracy like Deepl.

While it does have its limits (it's bad at generating natural sounding dialogue for example or coming up with variations), it is so far beyond any natural language AI I have ever seen,  it represents a quantum leap forward in this field of development!

There are a couple key points missing here. First the distiction between weak and strong AI. We have weak AI, it means AI that is task specific and can only operate within a framework where the parameters can be defined. Strong AI is also known as gerneral AI, it can operate intelligently everywhere, like we humans can do. It is not yet clear, also in part of metaphysical problems if strong AI is possible. (mind body problem) For strong AI to work the software has to performe relevance realisation, in other words -sort out the relevant information from the nonrelevant information. Since there is infitite information out there, strong AI runs into the problem of combinatorial explision. A task as simple as getting a glass of water in an environment without parameter constraints gets so complex that the best weak AI we have could not manage it. The second thing he misses is that weak AI cant have agency. It cannot "think" or "want" or "feel" -the reasons why are to much to elaborate on here. But looking up the chinese room form John Searle is a good starting point. 
But still I think we should not underestimate the power of weak (task specific) AI. It already has transformed our (post)modern (information)landscape.

A lot of this sounds like paranoia. A very important part about the kill decision that he skips over is the fact that HUMAN operators make tons more mistakes. From a numbers point of view an AI-confirmation system is going to be safer than a human confirmation system, so AIs can kill people, sure, but people are killing people way more anyways. 

The other thing missed that he actually mentioned, that doesn't get brought up enough, is that AI does not have mortality. We, as living human beings, think from the perspective of living things, and as living things we have certain fundamental needs we need to attend to, and whole social and economical structures to sustain that. We war for territory and resources, our drives to kill each other comes from a base survival need. Our mortality drives everything we do. But a machine is not mortal, it's not going to expire someday purely on age alone, it doesn't need to reproduce, it doesn't need to eat or sleep, it doesn't need to grow. What's more, at the end of the day, even if it did get somehow entirely shut down, it can just be turned on again some day and continue exactly where it was, less like death and more like sleep. It lacks those mortal drives that would necessitate a fight for survival, because nothing about its existence necessitates the notion of 'survival'. It would be an utterly alien concept to an AI to be concerned about its mortality. 

So at the end of the day, all this is the same as it always has been: Humans finding increasingly-clever ways to kill each other.
Letting a AI driven machine make the Kill Decision will be one of the greatest mistakes of humankind

Interesting.  Some of the more ominous elements strike me as exaggerating current capabilities and miss the mark on near-term risks.  A drone going rouge with its target selection algorithm will run out of fuel or ammo before too much damage is done.  And high-speed trading algorithms could be dampened with a transaction tax (assuming we had the necessary political will).  A much more immediate and overarching risk is no more sophisticated than bots on social media used to spread disinformation and to sow disagreement, confusion, and division.  Name any emerging technology: biotech, genetics, nanotech, virtual reality, blockchain, cryptocurrency, autonomous vehicles, etc....there is the potential for massive benefits, but also a host of unknown risks and ethical / legal / political quagmires that come along for the ride.  Society has a bad track record of dealing with these issues proactively.  And that history largely predates the degree of political polarization and widespread misinformation characterizing society today.   Our collective inability to agree on things like science, truth, and reality is our most pressing risk.  Without that, there's no chance of maximizing benefit (while proactively addressing the most significant risks) of any emerging technology.  I'll concede that the best on-line bots utilize AI.  However, if we resort to fear mongering as a motivator for action on the AI front, that just gives credence to the conspiracy theorists.

What the future holds, I can only speculate. However, this gentleman clearly doesn't understand current machine learning. The systems themselves DON'T write their own code. They use a neural net (more akin to the human brain's BASIC structure) and require a HUMAN to provide data with which the processing can be improved. It's a very fast, powerful form of 'trial and improvement'. Currently, there is nothing even approaching the complexity of a complete human brain. Each system has a specific, dedicated task at which it CAN surpass a human's ability. This has been true of non-artificial intelligent computers for decades. The military 'dog' is an advanced robot, but is not smarter than a human. It's processing is concerned with using sensors and limbs with multiple degrees of movement to traverse terrain. It is not sentient. It's similar to a self-driving car. There's no conscious intent. So far, they're all just 'very clever toasters'. The robots that interact fairly convincingly with humans are only SIMULATING conversation and human behaviour. There is a sense in which the software 'understands' conversation, but only by recognising patterns in grammar, semantics and sentence content. We don't have self-aware robots or software yet.

Humans cease to exist. The second most likely is really a continuation of #1, but a small minority of people cling to survival in a far more difficult environment on Earth or elsewhere, and maybe our existing human species survives and starts again, over much time. The third but extremely remote possibility is that we delay our self-destructive tendencies long enough to create our "next species iteration" that is somewhere between "human" and AI etc, and this post-human version survives after humans are gone. My most hopeful, but the most unlikely 4th outcome, is humans (successfully) genetically re-engineer ourselves and decrease our self-destructive tendencies and increase our traits such as empathy, and we survive and thrive. Change will happen whether we like it or not.  Who knows.

I feel like this guy confuses AI from movies with AI from the real world‚Ä¶ AI doesn‚Äôt think, feel or anything. It‚Äôs made for a very specific task. All it does it finds correlations. Feed data and it finds correlation between the time of the day and the brightness outside. Now humans have a very specific perception because our brain filters out ‚Äúunnecessary‚Äù information in real time. For example right now you focus on this text while ignoring the YouTube video suggestions. This filtering is very powerful and helpful 90% of the time. But sometimes it makes us overlook correlations. AI analyzes all data. And that‚Äôs how it figures out how a landing will be successful or not. But you have to give it a very specific task: check all this data and find what factors make the plane crash or land successfully.
From this alone it won‚Äôt act. Then  you need another program that uses the correlations detected by AI to land the airplane. This system will not suddenly ‚Äúdecide‚Äù to do anything else than landing an aircraft. For multiple tasks you need multiple AIs.

Very informative, but:
- Not 1M terabytes a day... Google+Amazon+Facebook+Microsoft in total only have about 5M terabytes in total, in all their servers, in all their datacenters
- People are behind the software, that's the scary part, not the software itself. It's people who decide what to make the computers do. Computers don't care and don't know. They just do what they're told.
- Google doesn't own DARPA (Atlas maker, actually Boston Dynamics is the maker that works with DARPA) - it is indeed a government financed group
- Most of this technology is only for military use and for a specific area - the huge resolution photo was taken by a military drone over a specific area, it's not a satellite that can see the whole city at all times 
- Drones do have AI to make the missions easier... but they don't "decide" to act by themselves. It's a human that starts and stops it, and controls it. The AI makes it easier to manage and control.
- Drones can "recommend" an action but they don't "decide"... that's a human's decision
- AI makes less "mistakes" than humans - just as described in the medical portion, they're better at it
- The same intelligence in a military drone is not the same intelligence in a smart watch - it's completely separate software, and they don't "talk" to each other like they're taking over... they can only talk to each other if programmed to do so, they are not sentient, they can't "think", they only do what they're told by humans. 

All that being said, we should be aware of the possibilities and put safeguards in place to protect and prevent against a dystopic future.

It's still humans who are the greatest threat. It's not AI that decided to put a cannon on a machine that was to be controlled by AI. It's not AI that has decided that the best use of AI is in maximising the profits of multi-national corporations. If humans used AI to solve the problems of world hunger, global pollution, poverty, etc, surely this would be a good thing. This whole way of thinking about AI creates a worrying misdirection by stating that the problem is AI itself, rather than the problem being the over-powered multinational corporations, who by nature of their immense size, make decisions in moral vaccuums, with their only guiding principle being profit-maximisation. Yes the prospect that AI can make a decision to kill or not to kill is scary, but let's not forget that it is making that decision, because humans have created it to make this decision. If the AI was truly autonomous it would be able to make the decision not only not to kill, but also would be able to decide whether it wanted to not partake in warfare altogether. I have never heard a convincing argument that has made me believe that a truly autonomous AI, in this sense, would have any reason to want to attack the human race. We shouldn't lose sight of the real enemy, which, more often than not, is either greed, or fear.

His description of AI, as being a piece of software and potentially hardware that has the capability to rewrite its own coding is not just wrong, but fictional. The term AI has nothing to do with software being able to rewrite itself. This idea of the singularity is something that probably connects with his description, But AI as a conceptual and more and more literal thing is a piece of software that has the capability to learn from the data it's given and adapt itself to the data, but no so much so that it is capable of rewriting the parameters by which we have designed it to operate within. It can adapt itself amazingly and truly acutely, but only a long the tracks the group of people who have created it's coding have laid down for it to move along in the first place. The idea that we would have any real interest in seeking out the creation of an AI that we would give the ability to rewrite its own coding is stupidity. Anyone with half a thought about this can see that would create a huge huge potential for something to go very wrong for us as humans. You have to remember, everyone who's doing this, creating and designing and coding these AI software are just as aware if not more aware of all these pitfalls as this man or anyone else who's gotten this elementary fear of AI. So they simply do not EVER attempt to design a completely not only autonomous AI, But almost literally omnipotent one. We can take very good care to make sure we just don't attempt to conquer the incredibly and likely impossibly complex task of creating a machine capable of changing its own operating rules and functions. The real tragedy is that while everything he's saying is true, we need AI and or advanced bio-engineering if we're ever going to mine our solar system or leave our solar system and branch out in the galaxy. A million to a billion years is being generous since there are various things that could lead to our extinction other than just AI or the sun dying.  If we're spread across the galaxy and manage to avoid war with other species then when natural disasters strike, we'll have colonies elsewhere totally unaffected and we'll survive.  If we're just on Earth, we're sitting on a ticking time bomb and that's even if we get rid of war or various other human-caused issues. Minor issues: ML is not only statistical tools, we have classical methods categorised as generative (probabilistic) and discriminative such as SVM, and bio-inspired approach such as ANN. ANN like MLP with one hidden layer is not deep learning, but a ML algorithm. Deep learning are ANNs based algorithms with multiple hidden layers / multiple layers, that's why it is deep, and usually used with huge datasets (CNN and RNN are good examples as explained in the video).  Transfer Learning can be done with a simple ANN (MLP), not only with CNN. Good Video!

DS is not just an overlap. DS is the superset of all. ML and DL are all data driven techniques. Right now we have very little AI that does not run on data driven techniques. So DS encompasses all that. Hmm may be AI can have a part outside DS in future like pure exploratory and conditional algorithms (which we don't have as of now) that does not strictly com under the DS set.¬†I rather see them not as subsets at all AI is rightly just writing smart programs, and ML is seen as the Enabling technology, ML has an issue with feature engineering so DL is seen as a enabler interns of automating that. ML and DL have a clear subset relationship, where as contemporary DS is a practiced profession like a set of best practices. I always used a triangular hierarchy diagram so I can be a bit vague when it comes to a subset relation. AI is engineering and programming, ML and DL is Stat and Math (though implementation uses programming), DS is a set of best practices that includes Math, Stat, computer sc. and domain knowledge. We are in the age of data ('driven') solution rather than just another software solution, some thing I do a lot to live.
